│ stop({"edit_points": [[1516, 1516,                                          │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineAndOrXor.cpp"]], "thoughts":    │
│ "1. **Understanding the Issue**: The bug occurs when transforming a logical │
│ AND (implemented as `select i1 %cmp2, i1 %cmp1, i1 false`) of two FCmp      │
│ instructions with different fast-math flags. The transformation combines    │
│ `fcmp ninf olt %x, 0.0` and `fcmp ogt %x, -0.0` into `fcmp ninf olt         │
│ fabs(ninf %x), 0.0`. When `%x = -inf`, the original yields `false` (because │
│ `%cmp2` is false, short-circuiting the poison from `%cmp1`), but the        │
│ transformed version yields `poison` (because `fabs` with `ninf` is poison   │
│ on `-inf`). The transformation incorrectly introduces poison where the      │
│ original was well-defined.\n\n2. **Analyzing `opt`'s Log**: The log shows   │
│ the transformation happens in `foldLogicOfFCmps` via `foldBooleanAndOr`     │
│ called from `foldSelectOfBools`. The key is that `IsLogicalSelect = true`   │
│ is passed, indicating this is a logical operation (short-circuiting) rather │
│ than a bitwise operation.\n\n3. **Root Cause Analysis**: In                 │
│ `foldLogicOfFCmps`, the range-check idiom transformation (lines 1516-1541)  │
│ does not check `IsLogicalSelect`. Unlike the ORD/UNO transformation (lines  │
│ 1459-1473) which has a `!IsLogicalSelect` guard, the range-check            │
│ transformation unions the fast-math flags (`LHS->getFastMathFlags() |       │
│ RHS->getFastMathFlags()`). For logical operations, this is unsafe because   │
